[1]The Igeler säule in the village of Igel on the Moselle is in addition to the Mainz Drusus stone, the only one at its original location since ancient times, above-ground preserved Roman tomb North of the Alps.
[2]The destruction after the collapse of the Roman Empire, escaped it by the fact that in the middle ages, the main image was held on the South side for a representation of the marriage of Constantius Chlorus with the Holy Helena, the mother of Constantine the Great.
[3]The 23-Meter-high arrow monument of red Sandstone was built around 250 of the brothers Lucius Secundinius Aventinus and Lucius Secundinius Securus for yourself and your deceased relatives.
[5]They show scenes from the everyday and professional life of a cloth merchant, as well as from mythology.
[6]The originally colourful monument was in memory of the dead in the family is probably the purpose of advertising character, the cloth business of the Secundinier in the city of Trier (Augusta Treverorum).
[7]A reconstruction of the column with the true to original painting is in the Rhenish state Museum in Trier.
[8]The tip of the Arrow is adorned with the sculpture of an eagle with outstretched wings.
[9]Today, it is weathered very heavily, and barely even as an eagle.
[10]From the Latin word for eagle, aquila, – the place hedgehog his name (cf. the English word "eagle" and the name Eigelstein).
